 speed.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1687440179143" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1687440179143" data-resolution="3000x3000" style=""><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/aa272754-bc34-4abe-8059-a489e7ddd81f/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/Stairmaster-in-Use.jpg" alt="Women Using Stairmaster" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="Women Using Stairmaster" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1684939924281" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1684939924281"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><b style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">4. Weight Loss</b></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1682422379488" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1682422379488"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Is StairMaster or treadmill better for weight loss? To answer this question one needs to understand what a metabolic equivalent of a task or MET is. MET is a unit used to estimate the energy expenditure or intensity of physical activities. In simple terms, the higher the METs, the higher the energy requirement of a specific exercise, thus leading to greater weight loss.</p><p>According to the Compendium Of Physical Activities, <a href="https://sites.google.com/site/compendiumofphysicalactivities/Activity-Categories/walking" class="" target="_blank">slow-paced stair climbing</a> has a coefficient of 4 METs, while fast stair climbing is worth 8.8. Research on the topic <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9309638/" class="" target="_blank">confirms nearly identical results</a>. Meanwhile, walking and running can go anywhere from 2 to 10 or more METs depending on the speed and incline. For example, <a href="https://sites.google.com/site/compendiumofphysicalactivities/Activity-Categories/running" class="" target="_blank">running up the stairs</a> is equal to 15 METs.</p><p>From this, we can conclude that, although treadmills are perfectly capable of aiding in weight loss, stair climbing generally has higher energy consumption rates.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1684949091654" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1684949091654" data-resolution="3000x3000" style=""><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/67e182e1-a606-4314-88a7-6fa7ea81b547/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/Performing-Stairmasters.jpg" alt="Performing Stairmasters" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="2328" height="1552" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="Performing Stairmasters" natural-width="2328" natural-height="1552"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685108520668" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1685108520668"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><b>Stairmaster VS Treadmill: Summary&nbsp;</b></font></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1687267632890" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1687267632890"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Looking at the treadmill vs stair stepper, each machine has positive and negative aspects you should be aware of before making a purchase decision. So, is the StairMaster better than the treadmill or vice versa? Here are brief rundowns on each machine’s pros and cons, which are especially applicable when compared to each other.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1687267661068" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1687267661068"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><b>Pros And Cons Of StairMaster:</b></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1685718313332" class="gf_row" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1685718313332" data-layout-lg="6+6" data-extraclass="" data-layout-md="6+6" data-layout-sm="6+6" data-layout-xs="12+12"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-6 gf_col-md-6 gf_col-sm-6 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1655122384504" data-id="1655122384504" style="min-height: 1px; display: block; flex-direction: unset; justify-content: unset;"><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685718313321" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685718313321"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><span style="font-weight: bold;">Pros:</span></p></div></div><div data-label="Icon List" data-key="icon-list" data-atomgroup="module" id="m-1685718313348" class="module-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-iconlist" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1685718313348" style=""><div class="module gf_module-left gf_module-left-lg gf_module--md gf_module--sm gf_module--xs "><ul class="gf_icon-list"><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="1" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1685718313348-1" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718313348-1" data-icon="gpicon-icon" data-ver="1.0"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(129, 215, 66);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-check-circle"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="1" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1685718313348-2" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718313348-2" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-exc=""><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Greater Muscle Development - thanks to the eccentric and concentric muscle action, stair climbing is generally better at developing raw strength, explosive power, and muscle size in the lower body. This makes it quite popular among athletes who want to develop their glutes and quads especially, but also hamstrings, calves, and core muscles.</p></div></div></div></li><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="2" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1685718313348-3" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718313348-3" data-icon="gpicon-icon" data-ver="1.0"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(129, 215, 66);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-check-circle"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="2" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1685718313348-4" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718313348-4" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-exc=""><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">More Compact - although they can be bulky, the general space requirement for a home stair climber is on the lower end amongst cardio machines, particularly due to lesser length.</p></div></div></div></li><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="3" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1685718313348-5" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718313348-5" data-icon="gpicon-icon" data-ver="1.0"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(129, 215, 66);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-check-circle"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="3" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1685718313348-6" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718313348-6" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-exc=""><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Calorie Consumption - thanks to the more intense nature of their workout, stair climbers have a higher calorie consumption rate, particularly compared to walking and jogging. This metric only gets close when comparing a StairMaster VS <a href="https://torokhtiy.com/blogs/reviews/best-incline-treadmill" class="" target="_blank">incline treadmill</a> max speed runs.</p></div></div></div></li></ul></div></div></div><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-6 gf_col-md-6 gf_col-sm-6 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1655122386485" data-id="1655122386485" style="min-height: 1px; display: block; flex-direction: unset; justify-content: unset;"><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1685718313399" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1685718313399"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><span style="font-weight: 700; color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">Cons:</span></p></div></div><div data-label="Icon List" data-key="icon-list" data-atomgroup="module" id="m-1685718313295" class="module-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-iconlist" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1685718313295"><div class="module gf_module-left gf_module-left-lg gf_module--md gf_module--sm gf_module--xs "><ul class="gf_icon-list"><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="1" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1685718313295-1" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718313295-1" data-icon="gpicon-icon" data-ver="1.0"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(221, 51, 51);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-close"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="1" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1685718313295-2" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718313295-2"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-exc=""><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Limited Upper Body Engagement - due to the nature of the workout, muscle engagement is practically limited to your lower body. When climbing stairs, the upper body mostly remains stiff and the arms stay in place to help with balance and stability.</p></div></div></div></li><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="2" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1685718346464" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718346464" data-icon="gpicon-icon" data-ver="1.0"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(221, 51, 51);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-close"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="2" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1685718346554" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718346554"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-exc=""><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Less Accessible - stair climbers may present some accessibility limitations due to their vertical up-and-down motion and higher impact. Individuals with joint issues, limited mobility in the hips, or difficulties with balance and coordination may find these machines less accessible compared to other options.</p></div></div></div></li><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="3" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1685718346177" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718346177" data-icon="gpicon-icon" data-ver="1.0"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(221, 51, 51);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-close"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="3" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1685718346209" class="element-wrap" data-id="1685718346209"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-exc=""><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Lower Movement Variety - while effective for targeting specific muscle groups, the repetitive nature of the movement of stair climbers can become monotonous over time. This lack of variety could potentially lead to faster exercise fatigue and may prompt individuals to explore alternative exercise options to keep their workouts fresh and engaging.</p></div></div></div></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1687268297119" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1687268297119" data-resolution="3000x3000" style=""><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/d04d5cc4-5d0f-494c-864c-bf392c27dbec/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/Using-Stairmasters-and-Treadmills.jpg" alt="Using Stairmasters and Treadmills" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1000" height="670" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="Using Stairmasters and Treadmills" natural-width="1000" natural-height="670"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1687267748724" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1687267748724"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><b>Pros And Cons Of Treadmills:</b></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1685718396384" class="gf_row" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1685718396384" data-lay